==German==
{{wikipedia|lang=de}}
===Alternative forms===
* {{alt|de|Santen||obsolete}}
===Etymology===
From {{inh|de|gmh|Santen|Sante(n)}}, from {{der|de|la|Sanctos|lit=(at) the saints}}. The spelling with initial ''X-'' first appears in Latin texts of the 10th century. One theory links it with {{der|de|grc|Ξάνθος}}, the gods’ name for the {{w|Karamenderes River|Scamander}} river near [[Troy]] according to the {{w|Iliad}}. This theory is based on the fact that there was indeed a well-attested mediaeval legend equating Xanten with Troy. The inherited local pronunciation is {{m|de||Santen}} /ˈsan.tən/, but it has now been widely displaced by the {{spelling pronunciation|de|nocap=1}}. {{m|de||Xanten}} is the only German locality in ''X-'' (though there are a few Bavarian ones in ''Gs-'', also pronounced with {{IPAchar|/ks/}}).
